 glycosylation via threonine\nsrc/ontology/go-idranges.txt:10505:GO:0018244\tMA\tN-linked glycosylation via tryptophan\nsrc/ontology/go-idranges.txt:10506:GO:0018245\tMA\tO-linked glycosylation via tyrosine\nsrc/ontology/go-idranges.txt:10519:GO:0018258\tMA\tO-linked glycosylation via hydroxyproline\nsrc/ontology/go-idranges.txt:10540:GO:0018279\tMA\tN-linked glycosylation via asparagine\nsrc/ontology/go-idranges.txt:10541:GO:0018280\tMA\tS-linked glycosylation\nsrc/ontology/go-idranges.txt:10578:GO:0018317\tMA\tC-linked glycosylation via tryptophan\nsrc/ontology/go-idranges.txt:10667:GO:0018406\tMA\tC-linked glycosylation via 2'-alpha-mannosyl-L-tryptophan\nsrc/ontology/go-idranges.txt:12511:GO:0035269\tBF\tprotein amino acid O-linked mannosylation\nsrc/ontology/go-idranges.txt:14418:GO:0030259\tMAH\tlipid glycosylation\nsrc/ontology/go-idranges.txt:17732:GO:0033575\tMAH\tprotein amino acid glycosylation at cell surface\nsrc/ontology/go-idranges.txt:17733:GO:0033576\tMAH\tprotein amino acid glycosylation in cytosol\nsrc/ontology/go-idranges.txt:17734:GO:0033577\tMAH\tprotein amino acid glycosylation in endoplasmic reticulum\nsrc/ontology/go-idranges.txt:17735:GO:0033578\tMAH\tprotein amino acid glycosylation in Golgi\nsrc/ontology/go-idranges.txt:19242:GO:0070085\tMAH\tglycosylation\nsrc/ontology/go-idranges.txt:21324:GO:0042076\tJL\tphosphate-linked glycosylation\nsrc/ontology/go-idranges.txt:21325:GO:0042077\tJL\tphosphate-linked glycosylation via serine\nsrc/ontology/go-idranges.txt:21792:GO:0042543\tJL\tN-linked glycosylation via arginine\nsrc/ontology/go-idranges.txt:22662:GO:0043413\tJL\tbiopolymer glycosylation\nsrc/ontology/N-terminal protein amino acid modifica:22:            protein deglycosylation 743          \nsrc/ontology/N-terminal protein amino acid modifica:25:            protein glycosylation 8861   \nsrc/ontology/ld.txt:15258:intersection_of: GO:0006486 ! protein glycosylation\nsrc/ontology/ld.txt:15260:intersection_of: GO:0006486 ! protein glycosylation\nsrc/ontology/ld.txt:15262:intersection_of: GO:0006486 ! protein glycosylation\nsrc/ontology/ld.txt:16918:intersection_of: GO:0006517 ! protein deglycosylation\nsrc/ontology/ld.txt:24914:intersection_of: regulates GO:0006486 ! protein glycosylation\nsrc/ontology/ld.txt:24916:intersection_of: positively_regulates GO:0006486 ! protein glycosylation\nsrc/ontology/ld.txt:24918:intersection_of: negatively_regulates GO:0006486 ! protein glycosylation\nsrc/ontology/ld.txt:31081:intersection_of: regulates GO:0033578 ! protein glycosylation in Golgi\nsrc/ontology/ld.txt:31083:intersection_of: positively_regulates GO:0033578 ! protein glycosylation in Golgi\nsrc/ontology/ld.txt:31085:intersection_of: negatively_regulates GO:0033578 ! protein glycosylation in Golgi\nsrc/ontology/ld.txt:42545:intersection_of: regulates GO:0006493 ! protein O-linked glycosylation\nsrc/ontology/ld.txt:42547:intersection_of: negatively_regulates GO:0006493 ! protein O-linked glycosylation\nsrc/ontology/ld.txt:42549:intersection_of: positively_regulates GO:0006493 ! protein O-linked glycosylation\nsrc/design_patterns/negative_regulation.tsv:1952:http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_1904099\tnegative regulation of protein O-linked glycosylation\thttp://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0006493\tprotein O-linked glycosylation\r\nsrc/design_patterns/regulation.tsv:2160:http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_1904098\tregulation of protein O-linked glycosylation\thttp://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0006493\tprotein O-linked glycosylation\r\nsrc/design_patterns/involved_in_x_y.tsv:529:http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0035977\tprotein deglycosylation involved in glycoprotein catabolic process\thttp://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0006517\tprotein deglycosylation\thttp://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0006516\tglycoprotein catabolic process\r\nsrc/ontology/ec_in_xref.txt:6030:relationship: part_of GO:0035269 ! protein O-linked mannosylation\nsrc/ontology/ec_in_xref.txt:23394:def: \"Catalysis of the addition of a galactosyl residue to a non-reducing O-linked N-acetylgalactosamine residue in an O-glycan.\" [EC:2.4.1.122, GOC:ma]\nsrc/ontology/ec_in_xref.txt:39204:def: \"Catalysis of the addition of the first glucose residue to the lipid-linked oligosaccharide precursor for N-linked glycosylation; the transfer of glucose from dolichyl phosphate glucose (Dol-P-Glc) on to the lipid-linked oligosaccharide Man(9)GlcNAc(2)-PP-Dol.\" [GOC:al, MetaCyc:RXN-5470]\nsrc/ontology/ec_in_xref.txt:39216:def: \"Catalysis of the addition of the second glucose residue to the lipid-linked oligosaccharide precursor for N-linked glycosylation; the transfer of glucose from dolichyl phosphate glucose (Dol-P-Glc) on to the lipid-linked oligosaccharide Glc(1)Man(9)GlcNAc(2)-PP-Dol.\" [MetaCyc:RXN-5471, PMID:12480927]\nsrc/ontology/ec_in_xref.txt:42358:relationship: part_of GO:0036066 ! protein O-linked fucosylation\nsrc/ontology/ec_in_xref.txt:69457:synonym: \"O-linked N-acetylglucosaminyltransferase\" EXACT []\nsrc/ontology/ec_in_xref.txt:73558:def: \"Catalysis of the addition of the third glucose residue to the lipid-linked oligosaccharide precursor for N-linked glycosylation; the transfer of glucose from dolichyl phosphate glucose (Dol-P-Glc) on to the lipid-linked oligosaccharide Glc(2)Man(9)GlcNAc(2)-PP-Dol.\" [GOC:ha, PMID:9597543]\nsrc/design_patterns/regulation_by.tsv:2140:http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_1904098\tregulation of protein O-linked glycosylation\thttp://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0065007\tbiological regulation\thttp://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0006493\tprotein O-linked glycosylation\r\nsrc/ontology/comments.txt:314:comment: Different forms of the complex differing in type of N-glycosylation of polycystin-1 can exist (endoglycosidase sensitive and endoglycosidase resistant).\nsrc/ontology/comments.txt:2310:comment: Note that GO:0004169 'dolichyl-phosphate-mannose-protein mannosyltransferase activity' (part of protein O-linked mannosylation) has never been observed in green plants. However, N- and C-mannosylation may occur in these species; see figure 1 in PMID:21558543.\nsrc/ontology/comments.txt:2657:comment: Note that the only known alpha amino glycosylation is on an asparagine; see UniProtKB:P58522. However, this feature is not differentiated from normal N-glycosylation of asparagine.\nsrc/ontology/comments.txt:4723:comment: This term should only be used when the binding is shown to require glycosylation of the target protein: the interaction needs to be tested with and without the PTM. The binding does not need to be at the site of glycosylation. It may be that the glycosylation causes a conformational change that allows binding of the protein to another region; this type of glycosylation-dependent protein binding is valid for annotation to this term.\nsrc/ontology/ec.obo:6030:relationship: part_of GO:0035269 ! protein O-linked mannosylation\nsrc/ontology/ec.obo:23394:def: \"Catalysis of the addition of a galactosyl residue to a non-reducing O-linked N-acetylgalactosamine residue in an O-glycan.\" [EC:2.4.1.122, GOC:ma]\nsrc/ontology/ec.obo:39204:def: \"Catalysis of the addition of the first glucose residue to the lipid-linked oligosaccharide precursor for N-linked glycosylation; the transfer of glucose from dolichyl phosphate glucose (Dol-P-Glc) on to the lipid-linked oligosaccharide Man(9)GlcNAc(2)-PP-Dol.\" [GOC:al, MetaCyc:RXN-5470]\nsrc/ontology/ec.obo:39216:def: \"Catalysis of the addition of the second glucose residue to the lipid-linked oligosaccharide precursor for N-linked glycosylation; the transfer of glucose from dolichyl phosphate glucose (Dol-P-Glc) on to the lipid-linked oligosaccharide Glc(1)Man(9)GlcNAc(2)-PP-Dol.\" [MetaCyc:RXN-5471, PMID:12480927]\nsrc/ontology/ec.obo:42358:relationship: part_of GO:0036066 ! protein O-linked fucosylation\nsrc/ontology/ec.obo:69457:synonym: \"O-linked N-acetylglucosaminyltransferase\" EXACT []\nsrc/ontology/ec.obo:73558:def: \"Catalysis of the addition of the third glucose residue to the lipid-linked oligosaccharide precursor for N-linked glycosylation; the transfer of glucose from dolichyl phosphate glucose (Dol-P-Glc) on to the lipid-linked oligosaccharide Glc(2)Man(9)GlcNAc(2)-PP-Dol.\" [GOC:ha, PMID:9597543]\nsrc/design_patterns/positive_regulation.tsv:1931:http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_1904100\tpositive regulation of protein O-linked glycosylation\thttp://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0006493\tprotein O-linked glycosylation\r\nsrc/ontology/imports/reactome_xrefs_import.owl:642:        <rdfs:label>Deglycosylation complex hydrolyses N-glycans from unfolded glycoproteins</rdfs:label>\nsrc/ontology/imports/reactome_xrefs_import.owl:14427:        <rdfs:label>CD274 N-linked glycosylation in ER</rdfs:label>\nsrc/ontology/imports/reactome_xrefs_import.owl:31307:        <rdfs:label>Asparagine N-linked glycosylation</rdfs:label>\nsrc/ontology/imports/reactome_xrefs_import.owl:31338:        <rdfs:label>O-linked glycosylation</rdfs:label>\nsrc/ontology/imports/reactome_xrefs_import.owl:34352:        <rdfs:label>O-glycosylation of 3a is terminated</rdfs:label>\nsrc/ontology/imports/reactome_xrefs_import.owl:34358:        <rdfs:label>O-glycosylation of 3a is terminated</rdfs:label>\nsrc/ontology/imports/reactome_xrefs_import.owl:35767:        <rdfs:label>B3GNT3 mediated CD274 glycosylation in Golgi</rdfs:label>\nsrc/ontology/imports/reactome_xrefs_import.owl:39631:        <rdfs:label>O-linked glycosylation of mucins</rdfs:label>\nsrc/ontology/imports/reactome_xrefs_import.owl:47816:        <rdfs:label>O-glycosylation of TSR domain-containing proteins</rdfs:label>\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:132:def: \"The Golgi cisterna farthest from the endoplasmic reticulum; the final processing compartment through which proteins pass before exiting the Golgi apparatus; the compartment in which N-linked protein glycosylation is completed.\" [ISBN:0815316194]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:4419:def: \"The rough (or granular) endoplasmic reticulum (ER) has ribosomes adhering to the outer surface; the ribosomes are the site of translation of the mRNA for those proteins which are either to be retained within the cisternae (ER-resident proteins), the proteins of the lysosomes, or the proteins destined for export from the cell. Glycoproteins undergo their initial glycosylation within the cisternae.\" [ISBN:0198506732]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:5038:def: \"A protein glycosylation process in which a carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative unit is added to a protein via the N4 atom of peptidyl-asparagine, the omega-N of arginine, or the N1' atom peptidyl-tryptophan.\" [GOC:pr, RESID:AA0151, RESID:AA0156, RESID:AA0327]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:5041:def: \"The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of an oligosaccharide-lipid intermediate, such as a molecule of dolichol-P-man or dolicol-P-Glc used in N-linked glycosylation.\" [GOC:dph, GOC:hjd, GOC:isa_complete, GOC:pr, GOC:rb]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:5043:def: \"A protein glycosylation process in which a carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative unit is added to a protein via the hydroxyl group of peptidyl-serine, peptidyl-threonine, peptidyl-hydroxylysine, or peptidyl-hydroxyproline, or via the phenol group of peptidyl-tyrosine, forming an O-glycan.\" [GOC:pr, ISBN:0879695595, RESID:AA0153, RESID:AA0154, RESID:AA0155, RESID:AA0157, RESID:AA0212]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:5044:def: \"OBSOLETE. A protein amino acid glycosylation process in which a sugar unit is added to a free alpha-amino or alpha-carboxyl terminal of a peptide.\" [GOC:jsg]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:5046:def: \"OBSOLETE. The glycosylation of a nitrogen atom of a free alpha amino terminal of a peptide.\" [GOC:jsg]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:6403:def: \"Catalysis of the transfer of sialic acid to an acceptor molecule, typically the terminal portions of the sialylated glycolipids (gangliosides) or to the N- or O-linked sugar chains of glycoproteins.\" [GOC:cjm, PMID:26192491, Wikipedia:Sialyltransferase]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:7222:def: \"A rigid yet dynamic structure surrounding the plasma membrane that affords protection from stresses and contributes to cell morphogenesis, consisting of extensively cross-linked glycoproteins and carbohydrates. The glycoproteins may be modified with N- or O-linked carbohydrates, or glycosylphosphatidylinositol (GPI) anchors; the polysaccharides are primarily branched glucans, including beta-linked and alpha-linked glucans, and may also include chitin and other carbohydrate polymers, but not cellulose or pectin. Enzymes involved in cell wall biosynthesis are also found in the cell wall. Note that some forms of fungi develop a capsule outside of the cell wall under certain circumstances; this is considered a separate structure.\" [GOC:mcc, GOC:mtg_sensu, ISBN:3540601864, PMID:11283274, PMID:16927300, PMID:3319422]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:8290:def: \"The chemical reactions and pathways involving extensins, a group of 60-90 kDNA hydroxyproline (Hyp)-rich glycoproteins whose polypeptide backbone consists of many repeats of structural Ser(Hyp)4-6 motifs, with heavily glycosylated 1-4 arabinose residues O-linked to contiguous stretches of Hyp residues, with most of the Ser residues being O-galactosylated.\" [GOC:tair_curators]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:10182:def: \"Catalysis of the addition of a galactosyl residue to a non-reducing O-linked N-acetylgalactosamine residue in an O-glycan.\" [EC:2.4.1.122, GOC:ma]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:10185:def: \"The stepwise addition of carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative residues to the initially added O-linked residue (usually GalNAc) to form a core O-glycan structure.\" [GOC:mah, GOC:pr, PMID:10580130]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:10186:def: \"The stepwise addition of carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative residues to the initially added O-linked residue (usually GalNAc) to form the core 1 O-glycan structure, Gal-beta-(1->3)-GalNAc.\" [GOC:mah, GOC:pr, PMID:10580130]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:10187:def: \"The stepwise addition of carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative residues to the initially added O-linked residue (usually GalNAc) to form the core 2 O-glycan structure, GlcNAc-beta-(1->6)[Gal-beta-(1->3)]-GalNAc.\" [GOC:mah, GOC:pr, PMID:10580130]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:10188:def: \"The stepwise addition of carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative residues to the initially added O-linked residue (usually GalNAc) to form the core 3 O-glycan structure, GlcNAc-beta-(1->3)-GalNAc.\" [GOC:mah, GOC:pr, PMID:10580130]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:10189:def: \"The stepwise addition of carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative residues to the initially added O-linked residue (usually GalNAc) to form the core 4 O-glycan structure, GlcNAc-beta-(1->6)[GalNAc-beta-(1->3)]-GalNAc.\" [GOC:mah, GOC:pr, PMID:10580130]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:11040:def: \"A protein glycosylation process in which a carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative unit is added to a protein via a C atom.\" [GOC:pr, PMID:7947762, RESID:AA0217]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:11171:def: \"The glycosylation of protein via the sulfur atom of peptidyl-cysteine, forming S-glycosyl-L-cysteine.\" [RESID:AA0152]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:11172:def: \"The glycosylation of protein via the O5 atom of peptidyl-hydroxylysine, forming O5-glycosyl-L-hydroxylysine; the most common form is galactosyl hydroxylysine.\" [RESID:AA0153]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:11173:def: \"The glycosylation of protein via the O3 atom of peptidyl-serine, forming O3-glycosyl-L-serine; the most common forms are N-acetylgalactosaminyl, mannosyl, galactosyl, and xylosyl serine.\" [RESID:AA0154]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:11174:def: \"The glycosylation of protein via the O3 atom of peptidyl-threonine, forming O3-glycosyl-L-threonine; the most common forms are N-acetylgalactosaminyl, mannosyl, and galactosyl threonine.\" [RESID:AA0155]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:11175:def: \"The glycosylation of protein via peptidyl-tryptophan, 1'-glycosyl-L-tryptophan; results in the formation of an (S)-2-amino-3-(1-D-mannopyranosyloxy-1H-indol-3-yl)propanoic acid residue.\" [RESID:AA0156]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:11176:def: \"The glycosylation of protein via the O4' atom of peptidyl-tyrosine, O4'-glycosyl-L-tyrosine; the carbohydrate is glucose, the origin for glycogen.\" [RESID:AA0157]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:11189:def: \"The glycosylation of proteins via 04 atom of hydroxyproline to form O4-glycosyl-L-hydroxyproline; the most common form is arabinofuranosyl-4-proline.\" [RESID:AA0212]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:11210:def: \"The glycosylation of protein via the N4 atom of peptidyl-asparagine forming N4-glycosyl-L-asparagine; the most common form is N-acetylglucosaminyl asparagine; N-acetylgalactosaminyl asparagine and N4 glucosyl asparagine also occur. This modification typically occurs in extracellular peptides with an N-X-(ST) motif. Partial modification has been observed to occur with cysteine, rather than serine or threonine, in the third position; secondary structure features are important, and proline in the second or fourth positions inhibits modification.\" [GOC:jsg, RESID:AA0151, RESID:AA0420, RESID:AA0421]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:11211:def: \"A protein glycosylation process in which a carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative unit is added to a protein via a sulfur atom of a peptidyl-amino-acid such as cysteine or methionine.\" [GOC:ai, GOC:jsg, GOC:pr]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:11248:def: \"The glycosylation of a carbon atom of a peptidyl-tryptophan residue.\" [GOC:ai]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:11316:def: \"The glycosylation of a peptidyl-tryptophan residue by the transfer of alpha-mannopyranose from dolichyl-activated mannose to the indole ring.\" [PMID:7947762, PMID:9450955, RESID:AA0217]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:14460:def: \"The stepwise addition of carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative residues to the initially added O-linked residue (usually GalNAc) to form the core 5 O-glycan structure, GalNAc-alpha-(1->3)-GalNAc.\" [GOC:mah, GOC:pr, PMID:10580130]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:14461:def: \"The stepwise addition of carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative residues to the initially added O-linked residue (usually GalNAc) to form the core 6 O-glycan structure, GlcNAc-beta-(1->6)-GalNAc.\" [GOC:mah, GOC:pr, PMID:10580130]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:14462:def: \"The stepwise addition of carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative residues to the initially added O-linked residue (usually GalNAc) to form the core 7 O-glycan structure, GalNAc-alpha-(1->6)-GalNAc.\" [GOC:mah, GOC:pr, PMID:10580130]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:14463:def: \"The stepwise addition of carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative residues to the initially added O-linked residue (usually GalNAc) to form the core 8 O-glycan structure, Gal-alpha-(1->3)-GalNAc.\" [GOC:mah, GOC:pr, PMID:10580130]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:16847:def: \"Catalysis of the addition of a glucose residue to the lipid-linked oligosaccharide precursor for N-linked glycosylation; the transfer of glucose from dolichyl phosphate glucose (Dol-P-Glc) on to the lipid-linked oligosaccharide Man(7)GlcNAc(2)-PP-Dol.\" [GOC:mah, PMID:10336995]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:18503:def: \"The transfer of mannose from dolichyl activated mannose to the hydroxyl group of a seryl or threonyl residue of a protein acceptor molecule, to form an O-linked protein-sugar linkage.\" [GOC:bf, PMID:9878797]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:19271:def: \"The process of transferring a fucosyl group to a serine or threonine residues in a protein acceptor molecule, to form an O-linked protein-sugar linkage.\" [GOC:sart, PMID:19948734]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:20259:def: \"The glycosylation of peptidyl-amino acids through a phosphoester bond forming, for example, GlcNAc-alpha-1-P-Ser residues.\" [PMID:7499424]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:20260:def: \"The glycosylation of peptidyl-serine through a phosphoester bond forming, for example, GlcNAc-alpha-1-P-Ser residues.\" [GOC:mah]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:20419:def: \"Catalysis of the addition of the first glucose residue to the lipid-linked oligosaccharide precursor for N-linked glycosylation; the transfer of glucose from dolichyl phosphate glucose (Dol-P-Glc) on to the lipid-linked oligosaccharide Man(9)GlcNAc(2)-PP-Dol.\" [GOC:al, MetaCyc:RXN-5470]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:20421:def: \"Catalysis of the addition of the second glucose residue to the lipid-linked oligosaccharide precursor for N-linked glycosylation; the transfer of glucose from dolichyl phosphate glucose (Dol-P-Glc) on to the lipid-linked oligosaccharide Glc(1)Man(9)GlcNAc(2)-PP-Dol.\" [MetaCyc:RXN-5471, PMID:12480927]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:20629:def: \"The glycosylation of protein via peptidyl-arginine, omega-N-glycosyl-L-arginine.\" [RESID:AA0327]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:22722:def: \"Extension of the O-linked mannose residue of a mannoprotein by the stepwise addition of further mannose molecules.\" [GOC:jl, PMID:19429925]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:24052:def: \"The chemical reactions and pathways involving dolichyl diphosphate, a diphosphorylated dolichol derivative. In eukaryotes, these function as carriers of mono- and oligosaccharide residues in the glycosylation of lipids and proteins within intracellular membranes.\" [ISBN:0198506732]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:29198:def: \"Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of protein glycosylation. Protein glycosylation is the addition of a carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative unit to a protein amino acid, e.g. the addition of glycan chains to proteins.\" [GOC:dms, GOC:dph, GOC:pr]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:29199:def: \"Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the glycosylation of one or more amino acid residues within a protein. Protein glycosylation is the addition of a carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative unit to a protein amino acid, e.g. the addition of glycan chains to proteins.\" [GOC:dms, GOC:dph, GOC:pr]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:29200:def: \"Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the glycosylation of one or more amino acid residues within a protein. Protein glycosylation is the addition of a carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative unit to a protein amino acid, e.g. the addition of glycan chains to proteins.\" [GOC:dms, GOC:dph, GOC:pr]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:33163:def: \"A process of protein N-linked glycosylation via asparagine in which N-acetylglucosamine is added to the N4 of asparagine, forming an (S)-2-amino-4-(2-acetamido-2-deoxy-beta-D-glucopyranosyl)amino-4-oxobutanoic acid residue.\" [GOC:pr, RESID:AA0151]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:33164:def: \"A process of protein N-linked glycosylation via asparagine in which N-acetylgalactosamine is added to the N4 of asparagine, forming an (S)-2-amino-4-(2-acetamido-2-deoxy-beta-D-galactopyranosyl)amino-4-oxobutanoic acid residue.\" [GOC:pr, RESID:AA0420]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:33165:def: \"A process of protein N-linked glycosylation via asparagine in which glucose is added to the N4 of asparagine, forming an (S)-2-amino-4-(D-glucopyranosyl)amino-4-oxobutanoic acid residue.\" [GOC:pr, RESID:AA0421]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:35697:def: \"The glycosylation of a protein by addition of N-acetylglucosamine via the O3 atom of peptidyl-threonine, forming O3-N-acetylglucosamine-L-threonine.\" [GOC:pr, GOC:sart, PMID:22158438]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:38114:def: \"Catalysis of the addition of the third glucose residue to the lipid-linked oligosaccharide precursor for N-linked glycosylation; the transfer of glucose from dolichyl phosphate glucose (Dol-P-Glc) on to the lipid-linked oligosaccharide Glc(2)Man(9)GlcNAc(2)-PP-Dol.\" [GOC:ha, PMID:9597543]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:38784:def: \"Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a protein upon glycosylation of the target protein.\" [PMID:26060076]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:43202:def: \"Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of protein O-linked glycosylation.\" [GO_REF:0000058, GOC:TermGenie, PMID:24509081]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:43203:def: \"Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of protein O-linked glycosylation.\" [GO_REF:0000058, GOC:TermGenie, PMID:24509081]\nsrc/ontology/go-definitions.txt:43204:def: \"Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of protein O-linked glycosylation.\" [GO_REF:0000058, GOC:TermGenie, PMID:24509081]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:1405:def: \"The Golgi cisterna farthest from the endoplasmic reticulum; the final processing compartment through which proteins pass before exiting the Golgi apparatus; the compartment in which N-linked protein glycosylation is completed.\" [ISBN:0815316194]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:16229:comment: Different forms of the complex differing in type of N-glycosylation of polycystin-1 can exist (endoglycosidase sensitive and endoglycosidase resistant).\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:37889:relationship: part_of GO:0035269 ! protein O-linked glycosylation via mannose\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:57181:def: \"The rough (or granular) endoplasmic reticulum (ER) has ribosomes adhering to the outer surface; the ribosomes are the site of translation of the mRNA for those proteins which are either to be retained within the cisternae (ER-resident proteins), the proteins of the lysosomes, or the proteins destined for export from the cell. Glycoproteins undergo their initial glycosylation within the cisternae.\" [ISBN:0198506732]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:60013:comment: This term was obsoleted because it represents the same process as protein O-linked mannosylation ; GO:0035269.\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:64393:name: obsolete protein glycosylation\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:64398:synonym: \"protein amino acid glycosylation\" EXACT [GOC:bf]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:64406:name: protein N-linked glycosylation\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:64408:def: \"A protein glycosylation process in which a carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative unit is added to a protein via the N4 atom of an asparagine residue.\" [PMID:35536965]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:64411:synonym: \"protein amino acid N-linked glycosylation\" EXACT [GOC:bf]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:64430:relationship: part_of GO:0006487 ! protein N-linked glycosylation\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:64452:def: \"OBSOLETE. The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of an oligosaccharide-lipid intermediate, such as a molecule of dolichol-P-man or dolicol-P-Glc used in N-linked glycosylation.\" [GOC:dph, GOC:hjd, GOC:isa_complete, GOC:pr, GOC:rb]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:64469:relationship: part_of GO:0006487 ! protein N-linked glycosylation\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:64474:name: protein O-linked glycosylation\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:64476:def: \"A glycoprotein biosynthetic process starting with the covalent linkage of carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative unit via a glycosidic bond to the oxygen atom of a serine, threonine, hydroxylysine, hydroxyproline or tyrosine side chain in a protein, which can be further elongated with the sequential addition of sugar units resulting in the formation of a protein O-linked glycan.\" [PMID:33775405]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:64477:synonym: \"protein amino acid O-linked glycosylation\" EXACT [GOC:bf]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:64488:name: obsolete protein amino acid terminal glycosylation\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:64490:def: \"OBSOLETE. A protein amino acid glycosylation process in which a sugar unit is added to a free alpha-amino or alpha-carboxyl terminal of a peptide.\" [GOC:jsg]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:64492:synonym: \"protein amino acid terminal glycosylation\" EXACT []\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:64497:name: obsolete terminal O-glycosylation\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:64501:synonym: \"terminal O-glycosylation\" EXACT []\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:64506:name: obsolete protein amino acid terminal N-glycosylation\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:64508:def: \"OBSOLETE. The glycosylation of a nitrogen atom of a free alpha amino terminal of a peptide.\" [GOC:jsg]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:64510:synonym: \"protein amino acid terminal N-glycosylation\" EXACT []\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:64776:name: protein deglycosylation\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:64780:synonym: \"glycoprotein deglycosylation\" EXACT []\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:80415:def: \"Catalysis of the transfer of sialic acid to an acceptor molecule, typically the terminal portions of the sialylated glycolipids (gangliosides) or to the N- or O-linked sugar chains of glycoproteins.\" [GOC:cjm, PMID:26192491]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:81009:relationship: part_of GO:0036066 ! protein O-linked glycosylation via fucose\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:92336:def: \"A rigid yet dynamic structure surrounding the plasma membrane that affords protection from stresses and contributes to cell morphogenesis, consisting of extensively cross-linked glycoproteins and carbohydrates. The glycoproteins may be modified with N- or O-linked carbohydrates, or glycosylphosphatidylinositol (GPI) anchors; the polysaccharides are primarily branched glucans, including beta-linked and alpha-linked glucans, and may also include chitin and other carbohydrate polymers, but not cellulose or pectin. Enzymes involved in cell wall biosynthesis are also found in the cell wall. Note that some forms of fungi develop a capsule outside of the cell wall under certain circumstances; this is considered a separate structure.\" [GOC:mcc, GOC:mtg_sensu, ISBN:3540601864, PMID:11283274, PMID:16927300, PMID:3319422, PMID:36266346]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:103680:def: \"OBSOLETE. The chemical reactions and pathways involving extensins, a group of 60-90 kDNA hydroxyproline (Hyp)-rich glycoproteins whose polypeptide backbone consists of many repeats of structural Ser(Hyp)4-6 motifs, with heavily glycosylated 1-4 arabinose residues O-linked to contiguous stretches of Hyp residues, with most of the Ser residues being O-galactosylated.\" [GOC:tair_curators]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:111609:def: \"The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of heparan sulfate proteoglycans, which consist of a core protein linked to a heparan sulfate glycosaminoglycan. The heparan sulfate chain is composed of the repeating disaccharide unit beta-(1,4)-N-acetyl-D-glucosamine-alpha-(1,4)-hexuronic acid, the former being either sulfated or deacetylated on its amino group as well as sulfated on one of its hydroxyl groups, and the latter being e a mixture of sulfated and nonsulfated D-glucuronic and L-iduronic acids. Heparan sulfate chains are covalently linked to serine/threonine residues (O-linked) of the core protein via a tetrasaccharide linker sequence (xylose-galactose-galactose-glucuronate).\" [PMID:27241222]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:111618:is_a: GO:0180064 ! protein O-linked glycosylation via xylose\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:123848:name: protein O-linked glycosylation via N-acetyl-galactosamine\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:123850:def: \"A glycoprotein biosynthetic process starting with the covalent linkage of an N-acetyl-galactosamine via an alpha-glycosidic bond to the oxygen atom of a serine or threonine side chain in a protein, which can be further elongated with the sequential addition of sugar units resulting in the formation of a protein O-linked glycan.\" [PMID:10580130, PMID:35536936]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:123854:synonym: \"protein O-linked GalNAcylation\" RELATED []\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:123857:is_a: GO:0006493 ! protein O-linked glycosylation\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:123868:def: \"OBSOLETE. The stepwise addition of carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative residues to the initially added O-linked residue (usually GalNAc) to form the core 1 O-glycan structure, Gal-beta-(1->3)-GalNAc, and ultimately forming the core 2 O-glycan structure, GlcNAc-beta-(1->6)[Gal-beta-(1->3)]-GalNAc.\" [PMID:10580130, PMID:33775405]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:123872:synonym: \"mucin type O-glycosylation\" RELATED [PMID:33775405]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:123884:def: \"OBSOLETE. The stepwise addition of carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative residues to the initially added O-linked residue (usually GalNAc or Core 1) to form the core 2 O-glycan structure, GlcNAc-beta-(1->6)[Gal-beta-(1->3)]-GalNAc.\" [PMID:10580130, PMID:33775405]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:123897:def: \"OBSOLETE. The stepwise addition of carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative residues to the initially added O-linked residue (usually GalNAc) to form the core 3 O-glycan structure, GlcNAc-beta-(1->3)-GalNAc, which ultimately forms the core 3 O-glycan structure, GlcNAc-beta-(1->6)[GalNAc-beta-(1->3)]-GalNAc.\" [PMID:10580130, PMID:33775405]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:123910:def: \"OBSOLETE. The stepwise addition of carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative residues to the initially added O-linked residue (usually GalNAc) to form the core 4 O-glycan structure, GlcNAc-beta-(1->6)[GalNAc-beta-(1->3)]-GalNAc.\" [GOC:mah, GOC:pr, PMID:10580130]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:133632:name: protein C-linked glycosylation\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:133634:def: \"A protein glycosylation process in which a carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative unit is added to a protein via a C atom.\" [PMID:35536965, PMID:7947762]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:133635:synonym: \"protein amino acid C-linked glycosylation\" EXACT [GOC:bf]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:134072:def: \"The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of keratan sulfate proteoglycans, which consist of a core protein linked to a keratan sulfate glycosaminoglycan. The keratan sulfate chain is composed of the repeating disaccharide unit beta-(1,4)-N-acetyl-D-glucosamine-beta-(1,3)-galactose, both of which can be sulfated. Keratan sulfate chains can be covalently linked either to an asparagine residue (N-linked) of the core protein via a high mannose oligasacccharide linker or to serine/threonine residues (O-linked) of the core protein via a core 2 type-linker.\" [PMID:29340594]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:134951:name: obsolete protein S-linked glycosylation via cysteine\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:134953:def: \"OBSOLETE. The glycosylation of protein via the sulfur atom of peptidyl-cysteine, forming S-glycosyl-L-cysteine.\" [RESID:AA0152]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:134955:synonym: \"protein amino acid S-linked glycosylation via cysteine\" EXACT [GOC:bf]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:134962:name: obsolete protein O-linked glycosylation via hydroxylysine\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:134964:def: \"OBSOLETE. The glycosylation of protein via the O5 atom of peptidyl-hydroxylysine, forming O5-glycosyl-L-hydroxylysine; the most common form is galactosyl hydroxylysine.\" [RESID:AA0153]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:134966:synonym: \"protein amino acid O-linked glycosylation via hydroxylysine\" EXACT [GOC:bf]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:134972:name: obsolete protein O-linked glycosylation via serine\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:134974:def: \"OBSOLETE. The glycosylation of protein via the O3 atom of peptidyl-serine, forming O3-glycosyl-L-serine; the most common forms are N-acetylgalactosaminyl, mannosyl, galactosyl, and xylosyl serine.\" [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK579918/]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:134975:comment: This term was obsoleted because it did not represent a specific process. It may correspond to protein O-linked galactosylation; GO:0180062, protein O-linked xylosylation ; GO:0180064, protein O-linked glucosylation ; GO:0180059, and protein O-linked GFucNAcylation, all of which may be linked to a serine in a protein.\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:134976:synonym: \"protein amino acid O-linked glycosylation via serine\" EXACT [GOC:bf]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:134985:name: obsolete protein O-linked glycosylation via threonine\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:134987:def: \"OBSOLETE. The glycosylation of protein via the O3 atom of peptidyl-threonine, forming O3-glycosyl-L-threonine; the most common forms are N-acetylgalactosaminyl, mannosyl, and galactosyl threonine.\" [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK579918/]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:134988:comment: This term was obsoleted because it did not represent a specific process. It may correspond to protein O-linked GalNAcylation ; GO:0016266, protein O-linked glucosylation ; GO:0180059, protein O-linked galactosylation; GO:0180062, or protein O-linked mannosylation ; GO:0035269, all of which may be linked to a threonine in a protein.\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:134989:synonym: \"protein amino acid O-linked glycosylation via threonine\" EXACT [GOC:bf]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:134999:name: obsolete protein N-linked glycosylation via tryptophan\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:135001:def: \"OBSOLETE. The glycosylation of protein via peptidyl-tryptophan, 1'-glycosyl-L-tryptophan; results in the formation of an (S)-2-amino-3-(1-D-mannopyranosyloxy-1H-indol-3-yl)propanoic acid residue.\" [RESID:AA0156]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:135011:name: obsolete protein O-linked glycosylation via tyrosine\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:135013:def: \"OBSOLETE. The glycosylation of protein via the O4' atom of peptidyl-tyrosine, O4'-glycosyl-L-tyrosine; the carbohydrate is glucose, the origin for glycogen.\" [RESID:AA0157]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:135015:synonym: \"protein amino acid O-linked glycosylation via tyrosine\" EXACT [GOC:bf]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:135143:name: obsolete protein O-linked glycosylation via hydroxyproline\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:135145:def: \"OBSOLETE. The glycosylation of proteins via 04 atom of hydroxyproline to form O4-glycosyl-L-hydroxyproline; the most common form is arabinofuranosyl-4-proline.\" [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK579918/]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:135146:comment: This term was obsoleted because it did not represent a specific process. It may correspond to protein O-linked GalNAcylation; GO:0016266, protein O-linked galactosylation; GO:0180062, or protein O-linked arabinosylation; GO:0180063, all of which may be linked to a hydroxyproline in a protein.\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:135147:synonym: \"protein amino acid O-linked glycosylation via hydroxyproline\" EXACT [GOC:bf]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:135349:name: obsolete protein N-linked glycosylation via asparagine\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:135351:def: \"OBSOLETE. The glycosylation of protein via the N4 atom of peptidyl-asparagine forming N4-glycosyl-L-asparagine; the most common form is N-acetylglucosaminyl asparagine; N-acetylgalactosaminyl asparagine and N4 glucosyl asparagine also occur. This modification typically occurs in extracellular peptides with an N-X-(ST) motif. Partial modification has been observed to occur with cysteine, rather than serine or threonine, in the third position; secondary structure features are important, and proline in the second or fourth positions inhibits modification.\" [GOC:jsg]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:135352:comment: The reason for obsoletion is that this term is equivalent to protein N-linked glycosylation.\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:135353:synonym: \"protein amino acid N-linked glycosylation via asparagine\" EXACT [GOC:bf]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:135360:name: protein S-linked glycosylation\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:135362:def: \"A protein glycosylation process in which a carbohydrate or carbohydrate derivative unit is added to a protein via a sulfur atom of a peptidyl-amino-acid such as cysteine or methionine.\" [GOC:ai, GOC:jsg, GOC:pr]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:135363:synonym: \"protein amino acid S-linked glycosylation\" EXACT [GOC:bf]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:135719:name: obsolete protein C-linked glycosylation via tryptophan\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:135721:def: \"OBSOLETE. The glycosylation of a carbon atom of a peptidyl-tryptophan residue.\" [GOC:ai]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:135723:synonym: \"protein amino acid C-linked glycosylation via tryptophan\" EXACT [GOC:bf]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:136425:name: obsolete protein C-linked glycosylation via 2'-alpha-mannosyl-L-tryptophan\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:136428:def: \"OBSOLETE. The glycosylation of a peptidyl-tryptophan residue by the transfer of alpha-mannopyranose from dolichyl-activated mannose to the indole ring.\" [PMID:7947762, PMID:9450955, RESID:AA0217]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:136430:synonym: \"protein amino acid C-linked glycosylation via 2'-alpha-mannosyl-L-tryptophan\" EXACT [GOC:bf]\nsrc/ontology/go-edit.obo:163770:def: \"The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of heparin proteoglycans, which consist of a core protein linked to a heparin glycosaminoglycan. The heparin chain is composed of the repeating disaccharide unit beta-(1,4)-N-acetyl-D-glucosamine-alpha-(1,4)-hexuronic acid, the former being either sulfated or deacetylated on its amino group as well as sulfated on one of its hydroxyl groups, and the latter being a mixture of sulfated and nonsulfated D-glucuronic and L-iduronic acids. Heparin is similar to heparan sulfate but it contains more N-sulfate and O-sulfate groups. Heparin chains are covalently linked to serine/threonine residues (O-linked) of the core protein via a tetrasaccharide linker sequence (xylose-galactose-galactose-glucuronate).\" [PMID:22566225]\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
